  "summary": "Joe Cragg, a thin-lipped blond man, argues with Calgary regarding the case of Jack Agglesden. Cragg contends that revisiting the matter is futile because Agglesden is dead and his reputation was already ruined by a history of swindling and embezzlement. Calgary counters that Agglesden had a perfect alibi, as he was being driven to Dreemore in Calgary's car at the time the crime occurred. Following the encounter, Calgary feels agitated and angry that no one seems interested in the truth, noting that even if Agglesden's widow did not love him, others should care about his innocence.\n\nCalgary later meets Christina Agglesden, a petite, mixed-race woman raised by Mrs. Agglesden, at a tea shop near a cathedral in Reddish Knolls. Calgary apologizes for failing to prove Agglesden's innocence during the original trial. Christina reveals that she did not trust or like Jack and never suspected him of killing his mother. When Calgary informs her that he has news that could clear Agglesden of the murder charge and potentially lead to a retrial, Christina invokes the Magna Carta, stating that no one shall be denied justice.\n\nFinally, Calgary visits Dr. McMaster, a retired man with bushy eyebrows and shrewd grey eyes. Calgary feels a sense of camaraderie with the doctor and explains his motivation for pursuing the case. He notes that despite his concussion and memory loss, he feels a logical necessity to address the situation rather than simply disappearing.",
